# No git / GitHub actions without explicit permission

**Default: hands off git and GitHub.** Implement code only. Stop when the code is done.

Do **not** run any of the following unless the user **explicitly asks in the current message** with clear git intent (e.g. "commit this", "push to origin", "create the PR", "open a pull request"):

- `git commit` (including `--amend`)
- `git push` (any remote, any branch)
- `git checkout -b`, `git switch -c`, or any branch creation
- `gh pr create`, `gh repo fork`, or any PR / fork / issue creation on GitHub
- Creating or pushing remote branches "to prepare a PR"

## Task wording is NOT permission

These do **not** authorize git commands:

- "in one PR" / "ship as a PR" / "PR this out" — means **scope the code change**, not run git
- "when you're done" / "finish it" — means finish **implementation**, not commit/push
- Drafting a commit message or PR description — write text only; do **not** execute git/gh

If unsure, **ask** or **stop**. Never "helpfully" branch, commit, push, or open a PR at the end of a task.

## Allowed without asking

Local **read-only** git when needed for the task: `status`, `diff`, `log`, `show`.

## After implementation

Report what changed in the working tree. Tell the user they can commit/push/PR when **they** want. Do not run those steps unless they explicitly request them in that message.
